# Add Pagination to GET /users

## Context
The `GET /users` endpoint in `src/routes.ts` currently returns all 15 users as a flat JSON array. The codebase already has test cases (in `tests/routes.test.ts`) that expect a paginated response shape with `data` and `pagination` fields — these tests are currently failing. The task is to implement pagination so all tests pass.

## Critical Files
- **`src/routes.ts`** — the only file that needs to change
- `src/data.ts` — in-memory array of 15 `User` objects (read-only, no changes needed)
- `src/types.ts` — `User` interface (read-only, no changes needed)
- `tests/routes.test.ts` — existing tests to pass (read-only, no changes needed)

## Implementation Plan

### Step 1 — Update the `GET /users` handler in `src/routes.ts`

Replace the current handler:
```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  res.json(users);
});
```

With:
```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start      = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(start, start + limit);

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

**Key details:**
- `parseInt(...) || 1` / `|| 10` gives the correct defaults (1 and 10) when the query param is absent or non-numeric.
- `slice(start, start + limit)` naturally returns `[]` when `start >= users.length`, satisfying the out-of-range requirement without any extra guard.
- No changes to `GET /users/:id` — that handler stays untouched.

### Math verification against the test data (15 users)
| Scenario | page | limit | start | slice result | totalPages |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Default | 1 | 10 | 0 | items 0–9 (10 items) | 2 |
| Second page | 2 | 10 | 10 | items 10–14 (5 items) | 2 |
| Custom limit | 1 | 5 | 0 | items 0–4 (5 items) | 3 |
| Out-of-range | 100 | 10 | 990 | `[]` | 2 |

All four `GET /users` test cases and both `GET /users/:id` test cases will pass.

## Verification
Run the test suite with:
```
npm test
```
All 6 tests in `tests/routes.test.ts` should pass (4 pagination tests + 2 single-user tests).

